###Quantifiers: suppose you want to mach 5 consecutive a's, you can write a regular expression as below ``` /aaaaa/g ``` but it is not very efficient, what if you need to match 100 consecutive a's, there is another way though. Quantifiers can help you in this regex, to match 5 consecutive a's, you can write a regular expression ``` /a{5}/g ``` to match minimum of 5 a's, you can write ``` /a{5,}/g ``` Notice that the above regular expression will match any number of a's more than 5, this is called **greediness**. to match maximum of 5 a's ``` /a{0,5}/g ``` to match 2 to 5 a's ``` /a{2,5}/g ``` ###`*` Meta-Character To match any number of a's, you can write ``` /a{0,}/g ``` Note that the above expression will match even an empty string. **The shortcut for this regular expression is `*`**, what I mean to say is that the above regular expression can be written as ``` /a*/g ``` ###`+` Meta-Character `*` matches even an empty string, to avoid it you can use the `+` meta character which matches a minimum of one or more instances of a character. For example, to match a minimum of one a, you can write ``` /a+/g ``` which is equivalent to ``` /a{1,}/g ``` ###`?` Meta Character: Any character follower by `?` meta character is optional. `/a?/g` is actually equivalent to ``` /a{0,1}/g ``` Note that it also matches with an empty string, but if the character we want to match is present in the operand string, it matches that character rather than the empty string due to **greediness**. ###`.` Meta Character: `.` matches any single character except line breaks, keep in mind that it matches with space characters too. ###Dealing with greediness of quantifiers: The quantifiers mentioned above (like `*`, `+`) are greedy i.e. they try to match maximum characters. Greediness is not the behavior what is desired for all cases, for example to match the html tags in the code below ```html

foo

``` You can write the following regex ``` /<.+>/g ``` but due to greediness, it is going to match the whole snippet of html above rather than matching with `

` and `

` only. To overcome greediness in the above case you can use `?` meta character like given below ``` /<.+?>/g ``` The regular express without trailing `?` matches with maximum character possible, whereas the regex with a trailing `?` will match minimum character possible. This is how we can overcome greed of quantifiers. ---------- ###Matching a set of character or range of characters i.e. Character classes: - You can match a set of characters using `[]` meta characters. For example to match either a, b or c; we can write a regex as ``` /[abc]/g ``` The above regex will match a single character whether it is a, b or c. To match any number of these characters (not empty string though), we can use `+` quantifier as below ``` /[abc]+/g ``` - The `[]` meta characters can also be used to match a range of characters, for example to match any single character from a to z, you can write the following regex ``` /[a-z]/g ``` - You can match the union of ranges of characters too. To match letters, digits and underscore character, following regex can be written ``` /[a-z0-9_]/g ``` **Note that most of the meta characters are not needed to be escaped inside square braces, also the order of characters in a character class does not matter**. ###`\w` `\w` matches with any single character whether it is a letter (small or capital), digit or an underscore. It is actually equivalent to the following character class ``` /[a-zA-Z0-9_]/g ``` Note that `\w` is not unicode aware and don't match with non-ASCII characters. ###`\d` `\d` matches with any digit, it is actually equivalent to `/[0-9]/g`. Note that it does not match with decimal point. ###`\s` It matches with any kind of space character, whether it be a tab or some kind of new line character. Note that it is Unicode-aware and matches some special Unicode space characters. `\s` is almost equivalent to `/[ \n\t\r]/g`. ###Negated Character Classes - `^` can be used to negate a character class, for example to match any character other than the
